nts make it through the screening process after submitting a <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/how-to-write-a-cover-letter/\">cover letter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/how-to-build-my-perfect-resume/\">resume</a>. Accordingly, an interview is a high stakes encounter.<!--more--> If you interview well, you may get a job offer. If you interview poorly, you probably will not get an offer. Going to your interview without preparing can be a bad idea. Here\'s our Step-by-Step Interview Guide to help you blow away the hiring manager!\n\nIn interviewing, as in house painting or marathon training or any serious endeavor, preparation is often the difference between success and failure.\n<h2><strong>1. Research Your Interviewers</strong></h2>\nInterviewers want to know that you know who they are. And <em>you</em> need to know who they are in order to represent yourself in the most relevant way. So before your interview, do your homework. This might be the most important part of this interview guide, so pay close attention!\n<ul>\n 	<li>Research your prospective employer on <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">LinkedIn</a>. If you know the names of your interviewers in advance, read their LinkedIn profiles. You may have experience and connections in common.</li>\n 	<li>Read reviews of your prospective employer on <a href=\"https://www.glassdoor.com/index.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Glassdoor</a> and learn how their salaries compare with their industry competitors.</li>\n 	<li>Explore your prospective employer and interviewers on <a href=\"https://twitter.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Twitter</a>. Read their tweets and what others have tweeted about them.</li>\n 	<li>Analyze your prospective employers’ web site to learn how the company views and promotes itself to the public.</li>\n 	<li>Dig into news articles about the company. (Start with Google “news” tab, then proceed to reputable sources like <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>The New York Times</em></a> or <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>The Wall Street Journal</em></a></li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000201 size-full\" title=\"Photo by Kelly Sikkema on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_notes_02.jpg\" alt=\"A fresh notepad is laid out with writing tools spread around it. The note-taker is ready to take notes on our interview guide. \" width=\"1024\" height=\"694\" />\n<h2><strong>2. Work on Possible Questions</strong></h2>\n<h3><strong>The Basics</strong></h3>\nEvery interview contains some version of the following three basic questions:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Who are you?</li>\n 	<li>Why do you want this job?</li>\n 	<li>Why are you qualified to do this job?</li>\n</ol>\nDo not be surprised or caught off guard by these questions. Prepare your responses in advance. Push yourself to think beyond the superficial or obvious (for example, “I want this job because I want more money” or “any job is OK with me”) and answer these questions as honestly and with as much depth and specificity as possible.\n\nThe following five strategies will help you prepare your interview questions:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Brainstorm your responses by writing for 5-10 minutes per question.</li>\n 	<li>Edit your responses to two or three sentences (<a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/networking-complete-guide/\">hone your “elevator pitch”</a>)</li>\n 	<li>Practice your responses aloud until you feel calm, confident, and natural.</li>\n 	<li>Rehearse your responses in a mock interview with a trusted friend or partner</li>\n 	<li>Memorize your responses. You can always go off-script or improvise during the interview.</li>\n</ol>\nIf you take anything from this interview guide, it should be that interviews are important and worth spending time preparing for. It is far better to have a rehearsed sounding response than an insecure, poorly thought-out response.\n<h3><strong>Anecdotes</strong></h3>\nMany interviewers will ask you to share anecdotes, which are brief stories that demonstrate your capabilities and attitude. Anecdotes help hiring managers get a sense of you as an employee, as well as your ability to think on your feet. Interviewers may ask you to recount:\n<ul>\n 	<li>A single project or work product of which you are especially proud</li>\n 	<li>Projects for which you were part of a team</li>\n 	<li>A task or project in which you were a leader</li>\n 	<li>An obstacle in your professional career and how you overcame that obstacle</li>\n 	<li>Your strengths as an employee</li>\n 	<li>Any weaknesses as an employee (Be careful with this one!)</li>\n</ul>\nPrepare these responses in advance. Be concise, specific, and positive. The last question on our list – “what are your weaknesses as an employee” – is tricky. The key to answering this question is to spin it into an opportunity to talk about something you did well. Oftentimes that means starting with a challenge you faced (your weakness) and how you learned from it.\n<h2><strong>Behavioral Interview Questions</strong></h2>\nSimilarly, some companies will conduct something called a “behavioral interview,” which seeks to get a sense of how you conduct yourself in the workplace.\n\nAccording to <a href=\"https://www.thebalancecareers.com/behavioral-job-interviews-2058575\">the Balance Careers</a>, typical behavioral interview questions include:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Give an example of an occasion when you used logic to solve a problem.</li>\n 	<li>Give an example of a goal you reached and tell me how you achieved it.</li>\n 	<li>Describe a decision you made that was unpopular and how you handled implementing it.</li>\n 	<li>Have you gone above and beyond the call of duty? If so, how?</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>“Do You Have Any Questions for Us?”</strong></h3>\nAt the end of most interviews, you will get a chance to ask questions of your prospective employers. Don’t just say “I don’t have any questions”! Not asking questions indicates a lack of curiosity, a lack of experience with how interviews work, and, ultimately, a lack of interest in the position.\n\nThe following are tips to help you prepare questions in advance.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Your questions should be substantive and inquisitive questions about the company and the specifics of the job.</li>\n 	<li>Do not ask a question that you could have easily answered by reading the job description or the company’s web site or by doing a basic Google search.</li>\n 	<li>Do not ask questions about compensation or benefits or vacation and sick days. <strong>Save these questions for human resources – after you have a job offer and are negotiating the terms of your employment</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000202 size-full\" title=\"Photo by Tim Gouw on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/tim-gouw-79563-unsplash_interview_women_business_01.jpg\" alt=\"A young woman in business casual sits in front of two woman. These women are interviewing her. The interviewee sits confidently, prepared by FindDreamJob\'s Interview Guide\" width=\"1064\" height=\"711\" />\n<h2><strong>3. Pick Clothes That Show You’re Serious</strong></h2>\nBe sure to dress appropriately to an interview to indicate the seriousness of your intent.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wear clean and neat clothing in which you look and feel serious and professional.</li>\n 	<li>Ask the people person or human resources contact who scheduled your interview what the dress code of the office is. If they say “business casual,” dress just a little nicer for your interview.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Men might wear either a suit or a jacket and tie with dress pants and dress shoes.</li>\n 	<li>Women might wear a suit or a jacket over a blouse and skirt.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n 	<li><strong>Do not</strong> wear jeans, t-shirts, athletic apparel, or any clothing with holes or rips.</li>\n 	<li>You can almost never be overdressed for an interview, but you can certainly be underdressed.</li>\n 	<li>It’s better to err on the side of caution, even if you are interviewing at a workplace with a casual dress code. You can always dress down <em>after</em> you get the job.</li>\n</ul>\nManners are as important as dress in an interview. Here are four etiquette tips that will give you an edge.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Brush and floss your teeth, especially if you have recently eaten.</li>\n 	<li>Do not arrive with a drink or food.</li>\n 	<li>Turn off your cell phone during your interview.</li>\n 	<li>Bring an extra copy of your resume in case your interviewer forgot to bring theirs.</li>\n 	<li>Bring a pen and a pad of paper to take notes during your interview.</li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000203 size-full\" title=\"Photo by William Stitt on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/william-stitt-111353-unsplash_runner_sports_01.jpg\" alt=\"A young, stylishly dressed athlete stands at his mark, ready and set to run a race. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2><strong>4. Get Your Head in the Game With These Proven Techniques</strong></h2>\n<h3><strong>Get plenty of sleep </strong></h3>\nThe night before your interview so you can get as much sleep as possible (and to relieve any night-before jitters), do the following things:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Go to bed early.</li>\n 	<li>Do not look at any screens (TV, computer, smartphone) before bed</li>\n 	<li>Do not drink alcohol or caffeine.</li>\n 	<li>Avoid stressful situations at home.</li>\n 	<li>Lay out your interview outfit.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>Be your best self</strong></h3>\nBefore your interview, summon your most positive, confident and calm attitude.\n\nTo reduce potential anxiety:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Do deep-breathing exercises</li>\n 	<li>Repeat an affirmation such as “I’m good enough for this job”</li>\n 	<li>Remind yourself “If it’s meant to be, it’s meant to be.”</li>\n</ul>\nDuring your interview:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Smile and make eye contact with your interviewers</li>\n 	<li>Listen attentively and do not interrupt your interviewers</li>\n 	<li>Speak slowly, clearly, and confidently</li>\n 	<li>Keep your responses succinct</li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000204\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/pete-pedroza-534409-unsplash_thank_you_01.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1064\" height=\"723\" />\n<h2><strong>5. Follow Up With an Email</strong></h2>\nSince the turn of the century, it has become customary for job candidates who have been given an initial interview, whether on the phone or in person, to send a follow-up email.\n\nAccording to <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-write-thank-you-email-after-job-interview-2019-4\">Jessica Liebman</a>, the Executive Managing Editor of Insider Inc., “As a hiring manager, you should always expect a thank-you email, and you should never make an offer to someone who neglected to send one.”\n\nWhy? Two reasons.\n\nFirst, a thank you email shows that you are actually interested in the job. Liebman notes that in her experience the candidates who were offered a job without sending a thank you email either turned down the job or quit after a couple of months.\n\nSecond, a thank you email shows the hiring manager that you are thoughtful, organized and well mannered. These personality traits are essential for a good team member, and they don’t always come through during an in-person interview.\n\nOne thing Liebman says you <strong>should not do</strong> – write a thank you note by hand and mail it to the hiring manger. Even if it gets to the hiring manager (it could get lost in the mail room), it won’t get there till after the memory of your interview has faded. And sending snail mail is so twentieth century.\n<h2><strong>The Last Word of our Interview Guide</strong></h2>\nThanks for reading our interview guide.\n\nIf you nail the interview and get a job offer, congratulations. If not, maybe the job was not a good fit for you. Start again by reviewing our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job/\">Complete Step-by-Step Guide to Getting a Job</a>. Remember that every interview is a two-way street: you’re interviewing the employer as much as the employer is interviewing you.\n\nWhatever the outcome, do not treat the interview as a judgment on your character or your entire identity. If you stumble or make mistakes, assess your performance honestly and learn from those mistakes in your next interview. We hope that this interview guide has helped you to feel confident as you seek employment!\n\nRemember: if you can get one interview, you can get another interview.\n\nAlso, if you thought this guide was helpful, please share it on social media with the links below!','Your Step-by-Step Interview Guide','','publish','closed','open','','step-by-step-interview-guide','','','2019-07-11 21:48:52','2019-07-11 21:48:52','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000196',0,'post','',0),(100000197,4,'2019-04-11 15:49:36','2019-04-11 15:49:36','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash','','inherit','closed','closed','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash','','','2019-04-11 15:49:50','2019-04-11 15:49:50','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000198,4,'2019-04-11 15:51:28','2019-04-11 15:51:28','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash01','','inherit','closed','closed','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash01','','','2019-04-11 15:51:28','2019-04-11 15:51:28','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000199,4,'2019-04-11 15:52:24','2019-04-11 15:52:24','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02','','inherit','closed','closed','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02','','','2019-04-11 15:52:33','2019-04-11 15:52:33','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000200,4,'2019-04-11 16:39:18','2019-04-11 16:39:18','','kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_NOTES_01','','inherit','closed','closed','','kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_notes_01','','','2019-04-11 16:39:18','2019-04-11 16:39:18','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_NOTES_01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000201,4,'2019-04-11 16:41:05','2019-04-11 16:41:05','','kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_notes_02','','inherit','closed','closed','','kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_notes_02','','','2019-04-11 16:41:05','2019-04-11 16:41:05','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/kelly-sikkema-642275-unsplash_notes_02.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000202,4,'2019-04-11 16:50:36','2019-04-11 16:50:36','','tim-gouw-79563-unsplash_interview_women_business_01','','inherit','closed','closed','','tim-gouw-79563-unsplash_interview_women_business_01','','','2019-04-11 16:50:55','2019-04-11 16:50:55','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/tim-gouw-79563-unsplash_interview_women_business_01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000203,4,'2019-04-11 16:52:47','2019-04-11 16:52:47','','william-stitt-111353-unsplash_runner_sports_01','','inherit','closed','closed','','william-stitt-111353-unsplash_runner_sports_01','','','2019-04-11 16:53:04','2019-04-11 16:53:04','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/william-stitt-111353-unsplash_runner_sports_01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000204,4,'2019-04-11 16:59:24','2019-04-11 16:59:24','','pete-pedroza-534409-unsplash_thank_you_01','','inherit','closed','closed','','pete-pedroza-534409-unsplash_thank_you_01','','','2019-04-11 16:59:24','2019-04-11 16:59:24','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/pete-pedroza-534409-unsplash_thank_you_01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000205,2,'2019-04-16 19:10:05','2019-04-16 19:10:05','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nTo get a job, you need to catch the attention of someone who can hire you – or at least point you in the right direction. Whether you’re applying for a job, prospecting for a job, or <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/networking-complete-guide/\">networking</a>, a cover letter is the best way to make your case in writing.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>What Is a Cover Letter? </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A cover letter is a professional document in which you introduce yourself and your qualifications to a prospective employer. You may also present your cover letter to a person who can refer you to a prospective employer. &nbsp; </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A cover letter should be clear, persuasive, and brief. Also, it should be no longer than one printed page (that’s around 300 words). There are several types of cover letters. But the basic purpose is always the same: to convince the recipient that you are a worthy candidate for employment. &nbsp; </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like all professional communication, a cover letter should be formal, respectful, and free from typos and errors. &nbsp; </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>There Are Different Types of Cover Letters </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cover letters come in three varieties, based on what you want to do. Each one requires its own approach and style. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3> <br>1. The Application Cover Letter </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nAn application cover letter is a basic requirement of most jobs posted on job sites, company sites, or institutional websites. \n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>How to write an Application Cover Letter: </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>First of all,</strong> <strong>Introduce yourself </strong><br>This is a major consideration of a cover letter. It might even be the most important point! Make sure to put your best foot forward.  </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Make an argument for why they should hire you <br></strong>Be sure that your argument is strong, and well stated. Because if you don\'t make a clear, concise argument and ask for them to consider hiring you, why should they? </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Support your argument with specific evidence </strong><br>It is important to note your performance at your previous workplaces. Once you are drafting cover letters or resumes, you\'ll need to reference your past victories to impress future employers. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Include information about your qualifications for this specific job </strong><br>Your education, training, or experience are what make you a valuable employee. Show the employer why you\'re the ideal candidate.  </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Explain why you want that job, and why the company or institution needs you</strong><br>This could be your one opportunity to be \'seen\' by a prospective employer. Clearly identify areas where your expertise would improve their company.  </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Also, you will usually attach your resume or CV (also known as a </strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curriculum_vitae\"><strong>curriculum vitae</strong></a><strong>). </strong><br>It\'s best to include your resume, so that the employer can quickly see your work history. This will allow them to quickly identify if you\'re an ideal candidate.  </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><br>2. The Prospecting / Job Inquiry Cover Letter</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You may write a prospecting or inquiry letter to a specific person or a specific company. This cover letter\'s purpose is to ask if their institution is now hiring or anticipates hiring soon.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like an Application Cover Letter, you should: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Introduce yourself</li><li>Explain why you are contacting the recipient</li><li>Highlight your relevant qualifications. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because you\'re not actually applying for a job, you need to explain your professional goals. Explaining your goals will help the recipient of your letter understand where you could fit within their company.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3> <br>3. The Networking Letter </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A networking letter is a request to communicate with someone whose experience and insight may help you find a job. They may help you either immediately or sometime in the future. You can send a networking letter to someone you already know professionally or personally. You may also use it to ask for a referral from someone in your network. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example, you notice that a friend of a friend is the hiring manager for a job you’re interested in. You can write your friend a letter, or more informally, an email asking for an introduction. Be sure to perfect your networking by reading our guide <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/networking-complete-guide/\">Everything You Need to Know to Master Networking</a>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>How to Customize Your Letter for Each Recipient </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cover letters are not form letters. Factual information like your education, geography, and basic employment history may be similar in every letter. But you should tailor each cover letter for the specific person that you\'re sending it to.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember, busy executives are looking for excuses to clean out their inboxes. Furthermore, intelligent readers can tell the difference between a personal letter and a form letter that gets sent to a hundred people. Because if your cover letter sounds like a form letter, it will be treated like junk mail and go straight to the trash bin. So, you should always try to create an original cover letter for each recipient.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4> <br>Here are two helpful tips to customize your letter so it gets read. </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip #1: Highlight the skills and experiences that are most relevant to the specific person or institution you are contacting.</strong> </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example, if you’re a journalist pitching an article to National Geographic you might emphasize your experience writing about your trip to the Brazilian Amazon. Because, if you’re pitching an article to Forbes, you might emphasize your experience writing about hedge funds. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip #2: Research the person to whom you are writing and acknowledge that person’s relevant experience and background.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example, if you are writing to a pharmaceutical branding expert, find out what drugs he has helped name. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>What to Include in Your Cover Letter </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cover letters are not as structured as a resume, but they do follow a format. People in the business world will expect that your cover letter follows these general guidelines. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><br><strong>Here\'s a list of what should be in your cover letter:</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li><strong>The Header:</strong> In a letter printed or uploaded as a Word document, the header includes your mailing address, followed by the date on a separate line. In an email, you would omit this information and begin with the salutation. </li><li><strong>The Salutation:</strong> Dear Mr. X, Mrs. Y, Dr. Z. Always use a person’s formal title. Do not use a person’s first name in a cover letter unless you already know the person well. For an application letter, if the job posting does not specify a recipient, use the phrase: “To Whom It May Concern.” A formal salutation should end with a colon, not a comma or a dash. </li><li><strong>The intro:</strong> This is one to two sentences summarizing who you are, the specific purpose of your letter, and how you knew to contact the recipient (for example from a job posting or a referral from a colleague or friend). </li><li><strong>Skills:</strong> Highlight the skills that are most applicable to the job to which you are applying and/or the company/industry of the person with whom you are prospecting or networking. </li><li><strong>Relevant experience:</strong> Highlight your professional experience that is most relevant to the job to which you are applying, and/or the company/industry of the person with whom you are prospecting or networking. </li><li><strong>The closing:</strong>While a cover letter is not a form letter, you can use boilerplate language in every closing. For example: “Attached, please find my resume for your review. Thank you for your time and consideration. I look forward to hearing from you. Sincerely, Your Name.” </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>Don’t Forget to Format Your Letter Properly! </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Formatting is the look of your cover letter including how big the type is and its design. Here are three rules of thumb for formatting your cover letter. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li> Length. A cover letter should be no longer than one printed page. Additional information (resume, portfolio, or work samples) should be appended separately. </li><li>Font. A cover letter should be written in a standard font (for example Times, Calibri, or Cambia). The size should be no smaller than 12-point and no larger than 14-point. </li><li>\nMargins. A cover letter should have 1-inch margins on all sides (Top, Bottom, Left and Right).\n</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>Add Only Relevant Experience to Your Cover Letter </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cover letters must also be concise. Above all, focus on your most relevant experience. Jobs in which you have performed the same or similar tasks as the job to which you’re applying or the industry in which you’re networking or prospecting. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Here are five things not to put into your cover letter:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li><strong>Experience that does not directly relate to the job to which you’re applying or the industry in which you’re networking or prospecting</strong>. Therefore, if you’re applying for a teaching position, emphasize your classroom experience, not the summer you shucked oysters and clams at a raw bar. </li><li><strong>Personal information that has no bearing on the job to which you’re applying or the industry in which you’re networking or prospecting. </strong>Do not mention your diet, health, children, pets, religion, or favorite sports teams. </li><li><strong>Any insecurities or doubts about your qualifications.</strong> Save those for your spouse, best friend, journal, or therapist. </li><li><strong>Negative comments about prior jobs or employers.</strong> Do not complain about previous jobs or employers. No matter how accurate or justified! Because this will always reflect poorly on you. </li><li><strong>Gaps in your resume and periods of unemployment.</strong> If nobody asks, then you don’t have to explain why you didn’t work for a year when you were twenty-five. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>Check Your Punchlist Items Again </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After you have composed your cover letter, go back and make sure you’ve correctly added these items. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Header:</strong> Return Address and Date </li><li><strong>Salutation:</strong> Title, Last Name </li><li><strong>Introduction:</strong> Who you are and the purpose of your letter </li><li><strong>Body Paragraphs:</strong> Relevant skills, relevant Experience </li><li><strong>Formatting:</strong> one-inch margins, 12 point font in a style appropriate for a cover letter </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>Always, Always, Always Proofread! </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A cover letter is a professional communication with high standards. Any error, even a small one, gives the recipient an immediate – and valid – excuse not to consider your request. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So before you email or upload a cover letter, run spell check and grammar check. Then proofread multiple times. If possible, print out a hard copy, since it’s often easier to notice errors on paper than on a screen. Read your cover letter aloud for any potential errors. Then, ask a trusted friend or partner to read your letter, since it’s almost always easier to catch someone else’s errors than to catch your own errors. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> When proofreading, think of the carpenters’ motto: “Measure twice, cut once. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> <br>One Last Thing…  </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nWhen you’re hunting for a job, it’s worth taking your time to craft a strong cover letter. You never get a second chance to make a first impression. And re-read our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job/\">Complete Step-by-Step Guide to Getting a Job</a> to make sure you\'re ready to win in the job market – from start to finish!\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','How to Write a Winning Cover Letter','','publish','closed','open','','how-to-write-a-cover-letter','','','2019-07-11 21:49:44','2019-07-11 21:49:44','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000205',0,'post','',0),(100000206,4,'2019-04-11 17:24:23','2019-04-11 17:24:23','A young man in business casual sits prepared for his interview thanks to our interview guide!','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02','','inherit','closed','closed','','johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02-2','','','2019-06-20 16:47:55','2019-06-20 16:47:55','',100000196,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000208,4,'2019-04-11 17:46:22','2019-04-11 17:46:22','Writing a winning cover letter is an art form. You should master this skill to help improve your job searches by getting selected for more interviews','luca-laurence-547660-unsplash_write_letter_cover','','inherit','closed','closed','','luca-laurence-547660-unsplash_write_letter_cover','','','2019-07-09 14:22:08','2019-07-09 14:22:08','',100000205,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/luca-laurence-547660-unsplash_write_letter_cover.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000209,4,'2019-04-11 19:21:10','2019-04-11 19:21:10','','ilya-pavlov-87472-unsplash_write_keyboard_work_job','','inherit','closed','closed','','ilya-pavlov-87472-unsplash_write_keyboard_work_job','','','2019-04-11 19:21:25','2019-04-11 19:21:25','',100000205,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/ilya-pavlov-87472-unsplash_write_keyboard_work_job.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000210,4,'2019-04-11 19:50:01','2019-04-11 19:50:01','','TSW_sample_cover_letter','','inherit','closed','closed','','tsw_sample_cover_letter','','','2019-04-11 19:50:01','2019-04-11 19:50:01','',100000205,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/TSW_sample_cover_letter.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(100000211,4,'2019-04-11 20:06:00','2019-04-11 20:06:00','','mari-helin-38313-unsplash_glasses_writing_letter01','','inherit','closed','closed','','mari-helin-38313-unsplash_glasses_writing_letter01','','','2019-04-11 20:06:06','2019-04-11 20:06:06','',100000205,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/mari-helin-38313-unsplash_glasses_writing_letter01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000212,4,'2019-04-11 20:12:02','2019-04-11 20:12:02','','adolfo-felix-546626-unsplash_write_study_work','','inherit','closed','closed','','adolfo-felix-546626-unsplash_write_study_work','','','2019-04-11 20:12:17','2019-04-11 20:12:17','',100000205,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/adolfo-felix-546626-unsplash_write_study_work.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000216,2,'2019-04-16 19:09:31','2019-04-16 19:09:31','Making the most of your job will help you survive the daily grind – and could help set you up for your next job.\n\nNo matter who you are, where you work, or what your future ambitions, you should make the most of your job. This means acquiring valuable skills, making professional connections, and also getting you closer to doing what you love.<!--more-->\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000218 size-full\" title=\"Photo by Cytonn Photography on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/cytonn-photography-604681-unsplash_handshake.jpg\" alt=\"A close-up of two hands clasped in a firm handshake, in the background is an office space and a woman is working at a computer. Etiquette will help you make the most of your job!\" width=\"1064\" height=\"710\" />\n<h2><strong>What Is Workplace Etiquette and Why You Should Care</strong></h2>\nThe first step in making the most of your job is to stop complaining about your job.\n\nThis may sound simple, but it is actually hard to do. People love to complain about their jobs, especially with colleagues at work. There’s a reason why TV shows like <em>The Office</em> and <em>Corporate </em>and movies like <em>Office Space </em>are so popular: they represent a funnier, sexier, more dramatized version of many people’s work experience.\n\nWhile complaining about your job at work may temporarily relieve your stress – misery loves company – acting disgruntled on a regular basis can hurt your chances of getting a better job in the future. Venting about work creates <a href=\"https://www.fastcompany.com/3032351/why-venting-about-work-actually-makes-you-angrier\">negative reinforcement</a> of bad feelings that affect how your co-workers see you – and how you see yourself. The negative impacts of hating your job are:\n<ul>\n 	<li>You appear unprofessional to colleagues and supervisors</li>\n 	<li>Your negative feelings are amplified</li>\n 	<li>Office morale suffers</li>\n 	<li>You are distracted from pursuing solutions</li>\n 	<li>Hurting your employer’s “brand,” which could hurt your resume</li>\n 	<li>Burning bridges with your employer</li>\n</ul>\nSo instead of complaining or being snarky and disgruntled on the job, focus your time and energy on making the most of your job. And plotting your next move.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000221 size-full\" title=\"Photo by David Preston on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/david-preston-513526-unsplash_bus_driver.jpg\" alt=\"A young woman stands in front of a school bus, wearing winter clothes. She is gazing downward, laughing heartily with her hands shoved deep into her pockets for warmth. These crisp winter mornings help her to make the most of her job. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"718\" />\n<h2><strong>Take the Job Seriously, Even If You Plan on Leaving</strong></h2>\nPlanning to leave your job? Join the club.\n\nThe average person <a href=\"https://www.thebalancecareers.com/how-often-do-people-change-jobs-2060467\">changes jobs 12 times</a> in the course of a career, and many people stay at their jobs for less than five years.  Few people work for a single employer for their entire career and retire with a gold watch as a thank-you gift for their service.\n\nSo if everyone’s busy looking for their next job, nobody’s doing their current job, right?\n\nWrong.\n\nUnlike politics, being a “lame duck” in the workplace is not a thing. Your responsibility is to work from the day you’re hired until the day you leave. If you don’t take your job seriously, you may spark conflict with supervisors and colleagues, making your current work environment more unpleasant and burning bridges for the future, whether you’re looking for a reference or recommendation letter.\n\nWhether you work in a large sector of the economy like retail or in something more exclusive like software engineering, the likelihood you will meet former co-workers in the future is high. Don’t ruin your chances for a better job by angering a co-worker who could be able to help you out in the future.\n<h2><strong>Set Expectations, but Deliver on Your Promises</strong></h2>\nA job is not school or a social event. The workplace is all about the bottom line.\n\nThat means you need to deliver, i.e. fulfill your responsibilities on time, every time.\n\nSound impossible? Not if you:\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>Manage expectations.</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Let people know what you can and cannot reasonably do</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n 	<li><strong>Negotiate deadlines.</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Unless you are a heart surgeon, most deadlines are arbitrary.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n 	<li><strong>Under-promise and over-deliver</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>People prefer to be pleasantly surprised that unpleasantly disappointed</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000219 size-full\" title=\"Photo by Bench Accounting on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/bench-accounting-49025-unsplash_life_work.jpg\" alt=\"A young man in professional attire sits as a long table in an office space. He is working on a lap top and has a bouquet of flowers and a small cactus as decoration. In the background, a window reveals a warm, bright day. These office perks help him to make the most of his job. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"711\" />\n<h2><strong>Maintain a Healthy Work / Life Balance</strong></h2>\nDo you live to work or work to live? No matter where you work, it’s crucial to maintain a balance between your professional life and your personal life.\n\nIf you work full-time, you may spend more waking hours on the job than you do off the job. That means it’s especially crucial to maintain boundaries.\n\n<strong>To maintain work/life balance:</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Spend time with family and friends outside of work</li>\n 	<li>Cultivate hobbies and interest outside of work</li>\n 	<li>Take mental health days, as needed</li>\n 	<li>Use all of your vacation and sick days</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Do not:</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Bring workplace stress home</li>\n 	<li>Feel obliged to be on call 24/7 to your job</li>\n 	<li>Bring domestic stress to work</li>\n</ul>\n<h2><strong>Make Deeper Connections to Your Workmates</strong></h2>\nAt the very least, you and your colleagues share the common bond of an employer and may also share skills, interests, and aspirations. When work gets dull or frustrating – as it invariably does – a cordial relationship with colleagues can be a lifeline.\n\nColleagues can also be <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/networking-complete-guide/\">valuable connections for future employment</a>. Odds are high that you’re not the only person at your job thinking about his or her next career move. It’s not uncommon for one employee to leave a company or institution and then recruit former colleagues for his or her new employer.\n\nShort version: cultivate relationships with your colleagues; you never know when they may prove useful.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000220 size-full\" title=\"Photo by NeONBRAND on Unsplash\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/neonbrand-618320-unsplash_mentor.jpg\" alt=\"Two men sit in a nondescript, white room. One of the men, who is significantly older than the other, is pointing to the screen of his laptop while explaining something. The young man\'s interest helps the older gentleman to make the most of his job. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2><strong>Ask Questions, Ask for Help and Always Be Learning</strong></h2>\nNobody likes a know-it-all. And nobody actually knows it all.\n\nOne hallmark of true intelligence is humility: realizing just how much you don’t know –even if you are specialized professional or are considered “the smartest guy in the room.”\n\nCultivate an attitude of inquisitiveness. You will learn more, and people will respect you more. A curious attitude creates the conditions for you to grow, which will benefit you in the short run <em>and</em> the long run.\n<h2><strong>Find Your Mentor, Be a Mentor</strong></h2>\nThere is always someone you can learn from at your job, and probably there’s someone at your job who can learn from you.\n\nMentors may be the most senior people or the most revered people or the ones with the most institutional knowledge. They may also be largely unacknowledged people that you respect and you connect with.\n\nOn the flip side, identify people who might benefit from your expertise and offer to be their mentor. In the short term, helping other people will give you a sense of purpose and a sense of your own value. Mentoring may also benefit you in the long run. People tend to remember their mentors. And someone you mentor today may be in a position to help you tomorrow.\n\nAs best-selling author Ryan Holiday <a href=\"https://99u.adobe.com/articles/36393/how-to-find-a-mentor\">says</a>, “mentorship, like all relationships, is a process, not an accomplishment.” By demonstrating your ability to help others, you will create goodwill with people at your job who are in a position to help you.\n\nIf you are dedicated to always learning, you will be open to help that’s offered when you need it.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000222 size-full\" title=\"alexandra-kirr-322679-unsplash_joy_job\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alexandra-kirr-322679-unsplash_joy_job.jpg\" alt=\"A fashionable young woman stands in front of a busy cafe, her head tilted back as she laughs. Behind her is a long avenue with cars and people moving about. Getting out of the office for a walk helps her to make the most of her job. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2><strong>Start Developing Skills to do What you Love</strong></h2>\nWhatever your dream, you can probably apply skills from your workplace to pursue that dream.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Are you copywriting for a corporation? Apply those literary skills to write your Netflix series or true crime podcast.</li>\n 	<li>Take career development classes to expand your expertise. Often employers will pay for these classes as part of their benefits package.</li>\n 	<li>Are you pitching deals to investors? Write a business plan for your own start-up.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2><strong>The Last Word</strong></h2>\nYour job is a word, not a sentence. Making the best of your job now will go a long way toward boosting your happiness and future prospects. To help you get that new and better job, review our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job/\">Complete Step-by-Step Guide to Getting a Job</a> to put yourself on the path to a happier place – today.','How to Make the Most of Your Job','','publish','closed','open','','how-to-make-the-most-of-your-job','','','2019-07-11 21:49:34','2019-07-11 21:49:34','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000216',0,'post','',0),(100000217,4,'2019-04-12 21:24:00','2019-04-12 21:24:00','','linkedin-sales-navigator-402831-unsplash_happy_office','','inherit','closed','closed','','linkedin-sales-navigator-402831-unsplash_happy_office','','','2019-06-21 12:13:02','2019-06-21 12:13:02','',100000216,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/linkedin-sales-navigator-402831-unsplash_happy_office.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000218,4,'2019-04-12 21:36:13','2019-04-12 21:36:13','','cytonn-photography-604681-unsplash_handshake','','inherit','closed','closed','','cytonn-photography-604681-unsplash_handshake','','','2019-04-12 21:36:19','2019-04-12 21:36:19','',100000216,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/cytonn-photography-604681-unsplash_handshake.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000219,4,'2019-04-12 21:38:07','2019-04-12 21:38:07','','bench-accounting-49025-unsplash_life_work','','inherit','closed','closed','','bench-accounting-49025-unsplash_life_work','','','2019-04-12 21:38:29','2019-04-12 21:38:29','',100000216,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/bench-accounting-49025-unsplash_life_work.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000220,4,'2019-04-12 21:39:43','2019-04-12 21:39:43','','neonbrand-618320-unsplash_mentor','','inherit','closed','closed','','neonbrand-618320-unsplash_mentor','','','2019-04-12 21:39:57','2019-04-12 21:39:57','',100000216,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/neonbrand-618320-unsplash_mentor.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000221,4,'2019-04-12 21:47:01','2019-04-12 21:47:01','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','david-preston-513526-unsplash_bus_driver','','','2019-04-12 21:47:14','2019-04-12 21:47:14','',100000216,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/david-preston-513526-unsplash_bus_driver.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000222,4,'2019-04-12 21:56:14','2019-04-12 21:56:14','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','alexandra-kirr-322679-unsplash_joy_job','','','2019-04-12 21:56:30','2019-04-12 21:56:30','',100000216,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alexandra-kirr-322679-unsplash_joy_job.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000224,2,'2019-04-16 19:09:03','2019-04-16 19:09:03','Networking is your secret weapon – a weapon that is hiding in plain sight.\n\nWhen you need to find a job, aside from your basic qualifications, there is no more powerful tool at your disposal than your social and professional network: family, friends, acquaintances, and colleagues – not to mention<!--more--> everyone those people know! If all the people on earth are only six degrees from Kevin Bacon, you are likely only one or two degrees of separation away from someone who can help you land a job.\n\nSo start working your network to jump-start your career!\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000231 size-full\" title=\"nordwood-themes-359015-unsplash_social_media_networking\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/nordwood-themes-359015-unsplash_social_media_networking.jpg\" alt=\"Someone\'s hands grasp an iPad. They\'re using the iPad for social networking\" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2><strong>Social Media Is Your Go-to Networking Tool</strong></h2>\nSites like <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">LinkedIn</a> are focused primarily on professional networking and cater specifically to employers and job seekers.  But if you use a social media account like <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Facebook</a>, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Twitter</a>, or <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Instagram</a>, you are also networking. It’s no accident that these platforms are also called social networks. Every time you post words, images, or videos online, you are declaring something about yourself to all of your connections –and likely informing more people than you realize.\n\nThough LinkedIn has positioned itself for 15 years as the online social network for employers and job seekers, Facebook also has resources for people looking for a job. Facebook groups like <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/JOBOpportunitiesandCareersinUSA\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Job Opportunities &amp; Careers in the USA</a> are a great way to meet people in your industry  – or in an industry you want to be in.\n\nIn addition to posting about your vacation, pets, children, and your favorite brands...\n<h2>How to use social media for Networking:</h2>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Share your professional accomplishments, milestones, and goals</li>\n 	<li>Learn about job opportunities by following companies’ social media accounts</li>\n 	<li>Connect with people who may refer or hire you for a job</li>\n 	<li>Promote your personal “brand”</li>\n 	<li>Find inspiration from other people and their successes</li>\n 	<li>Help other people find work (karma)</li>\n</ul>\nWhile it’s useful to post actively on social media when you are seeking work, the savviest and most successful networkers post this type of information constantly. To really win at networking, you never rest on your laurels – you are always looking for your next job. In a competitive marketplace – especially if you are a freelancer – it’s never a bad idea to cultivate connections for the future.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000232 size-full\" title=\"glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer.jpg\" alt=\"Someone uses a laptop to help them while networking. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"708\" />\n<h2></h2>\n<h2><strong>Asking For (and Write!) Recommendations</strong></h2>\nIn a competitive marketplace, a written recommendation can give you the edge over another candidate with similar qualifications. Letters of reference lend authority and credibility to your candidacy. Employers put extra value on someone else\'s recommendation of you, especially if your recommender holds a position of authority, power, or esteem.\n<h3></h3>\n<h3><strong>People you want to write you recommendations include:</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n 	<li>A prior teacher or professor</li>\n 	<li>A former or current supervisor from a job</li>\n 	<li>A current client, if you are a freelancer</li>\n 	<li>A professional colleague who can testify to the quality of your work</li>\n</ul>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3><strong>People you do not want to write you recommendations include:</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n 	<li>A spouse or romantic partner</li>\n 	<li>A family member</li>\n 	<li>Friends who don\'t know you from work</li>\n 	<li>People with whom you have had negative experiences</li>\n 	<li>Those who do not know you or your work well</li>\n</ul>\nThough your family and friends know you well, they don\'t necessarily know you in a work context. What\'s more, employers don\'t consider them unbiased sources of information – even if you work together in a family business!\n<h3></h3>\n<h3><strong>How and when to write a recommendation for networking:</strong></h3>\nYou should agree to write a recommendation for someone only if you have strong positive feelings about the person and their work. If you don’t, respectfully decline. It’s better to risk hurt feelings than to write a lukewarm (or insincere) recommendation.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000233 size-full\" title=\"monica-melton-467245-unsplash_mentor\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/monica-melton-467245-unsplash_mentor.jpg\" alt=\"A young woman sits at a networking event. She speaks with an older gentleman who could be a potential mentor. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2></h2>\n<h2><strong>Find a Mentor (or Be One)</strong></h2>\nSuccessful professionals rarely succeed in isolation. Instead, they actively ask more experienced people for help and guidance. If you read biographies, you will notice how often successful people credit a mentor, often multiple mentors, for their success. Those mentors might be parents, teachers, or coaches, professors, colleagues, or supervisors. They might be anyone else with something valuable to teach.\n<h3></h3>\n<h3><strong>These are the best people to be potential mentors in your network:</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Choose someone with a personality that speaks to you</li>\n 	<li>Someone who has skills or proven success in an area you are interested in</li>\n 	<li>Those who have expressed interest in you and your success</li>\n</ul>\nMentors don\'t have to be someone you work with. In fact, the best mentors may be people who don\'t even work in your industry or area of specialization. Part of a mentor\'s job is to help open doors for you with employers, but more often, a mentor is there to give you solid career advice. <strong>Remember:</strong> good advice often comes from being able to see old problems in a new way.\n\nOnce you identify your potential mentors, write a <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/how-to-write-a-cover-letter/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>networking cover letter</strong></a>.\n<h2></h2>\n<h2><strong>How to Get the Right Person to Read Your Emails</strong></h2>\nE-mail is a black hole. Do not blindly send a networking email to someone you have never met or someone who is not expecting to hear from you. Instead, ask a mutual acquaintance for an e-introduction.\n\nThis is where your social media research comes in handy. If you have worked in the same industry or have gone to the same school as the person you want to email, Facebook and LinkedIn will tell you how many people you have in common or the degrees of separation between you and them. Find a mutual connection that you know well enough to email, and ask that person to put you in touch with your target audience.\n<h2></h2>\n<h2>Calling is great for professional networking</h2>\nIt might sound old fashioned, but picking up the phone and calling a person really works.  If you get a voicemail, leave a message. If you reach an assistant, be friendly and make your case. Since the turn of the century, it has become easier for us to send emails to hundreds and hundreds of people we don\'t know. The result has been a loss of personal connection that many people miss.\n\nBy using the phone to talk person to person, you will set yourself apart from the crowd, and you\'ll create a bond between yourself and the person you\'re trying to impress. But be sure to call their work number, and only during office hours! The success of this technique can backfire if you act like a telemarketer.\n<h2><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000234 size-full\" title=\"jobz-tyler-1397802-unsplash_elevator_pitch\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/jobz-tyler-1397802-unsplash_elevator_pitch.jpg\" alt=\"A smartly dressed young man exits a networking event with a confident expression on his face. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"756\" /></h2>\n<h2><strong>Perfect Your Elevator Pitch</strong></h2>\nIn Hollywood, writers, directors, and producers all hone their “elevator pitch” – a brief, catchy, and enticing summary of a movie that can be delivered as you ride together in an elevator.  “It’s like <em>Jaws</em> meets <em>King Lear</em>, but set in Russia on the eve of the Bolshevik revolution.”\n\nSimilarly, if you’re looking for a job, you should have an elevator pitch that summarizes your skills, experience, and goals.  Your elevator pitch may be similar to an objective statement or branding statement that appears on the top of your resume, or a sentence that appears in the first paragraph of your cover letter.\n\nMarisa Sanfilippo <a href=\"https://www.businessnewsdaily.com/4034-elevator-pitch-tips.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">suggests</a> the following seven tips for business people perfecting their elevator pitches, but you can also use them for your job search:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Be able to express what makes you different in a sentence or two.</li>\n 	<li>Know who you\'re talking to so you can craft your message to their interests.</li>\n 	<li>Know the key selling point that makes you the best candidate for the job.</li>\n 	<li>Open and close with your name so the person you\'re speaking to remembers you!</li>\n 	<li>Don\'t be nervous! Speak clearly and in a conversational tone.</li>\n 	<li>Test your pitch out on the mirror, your friends, family, and pets.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2><strong>Ask the Right Questions</strong></h2>\nWhen networking, always be respectful of people you contact. No one wants to feel like they\'re just a tool in your toolbox.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Be genuinely curious</li>\n 	<li>Always be humble: you may not even know what you don’t know</li>\n 	<li>Have respect for the person’s expertise</li>\n 	<li>Take the long view (as opposed to expecting immediate results)</li>\n</ul>\nDon\'t ask questions you could answer easily with basic online research or make unrealistic requests (Get me a $100K job with benefits by Friday!). Knowing how to ask the right questions is a mix of knowing how to really listen to what people are saying and knowing how to tell them you need to know more.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100000235 size-full\" title=\"marten-newhall-226045-unsplash_eyes_suit_glass\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/marten-newhall-226045-unsplash_eyes_suit_glass.jpg\" alt=\"A young man in a pinstripe suit holds a magnifying glass to his face to symbolize his search for a network. \" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2><strong>Eyes on the Prize while Networking</strong></h2>\nWhen you’re networking, it’s crucial to stay focused on your goal. This is no time for shyness or false pride. One thing is certain – if you don’t ask, it\'s unlikely you will get help. Most people aren\'t mind readers.\n\nDo your homework, prepare your elevator pitch, and ask the right questions to the right people. Go back and review our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job/\">Complete Step-by-Step Guide to Getting a Job</a>. Your social and professional network is an invaluable tool for landing a job. Cultivate your network wisely and use it strategically and you will reap the benefits.','Everything You Need to Know to Master Networking','','publish','closed','open','','networking-complete-guide','','','2019-07-11 21:49:26','2019-07-11 21:49:26','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000224',0,'post','',0),(100000225,2,'2019-04-16 19:08:14','2019-04-16 19:08:14','<span data-offset-key=\"2ggjv-0-0\">Writing a perfect resume can be difficult, no matter how old you are or how much experience you have. It forces you to distill your professional and educational experience. Your resume should be a compelling one-page document. You must do this all while obeying standard conventions and forms. </span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"2ggjv-1-0\">Finally, also make a strong enough impression to <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/12-ways-to-make-your-resume-stand-out-2014-4\">distinguish yourself from a crowd</a> of other applicants who may qualify</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"2ggjv-2-0\">.</span><!--more-->\n<h1>What Makes a Perfect Resume?</h1>\nThe most essential and compelling parts of your resume are:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Your underlying professional experience</li>\n 	<li>Your education</li>\n 	<li>The skills you possess</li>\n</ol>\nThe stronger your work and schooling, the better positioned you are to find a job.\n\n<strong>Remember:</strong><span data-offset-key=\"3v523-0-1\"> resumes serve as an initial screen. </span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"3v523-1-0\">They help employers to select a handful of qualified applicants from a larger pool of unqualified applicants</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"3v523-2-0\">. It is typical for employers to receive more resumes than they can review. So the default response to a resume is a speedy rejection.</span>\n\n<hr />\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?\">Find Your Dream Job</a></p>\n\n\n<hr />\n\nFurthermore, employers rarely bother to let you know your status. They will also rarely respond to your inquiries for an update. Typical employers have a “don’t call us, we’ll call you” policy. Or, if you prefer an analogy from country music: “if the phone don’t ring, you\'ll know it’s me.” The best you’ll get will likely be a form letter rejection, so no matter what happens, don’t get discouraged! <a href=\"https://www.themuse.com/advice/this-is-the-email-smart-people-send-when-theyre-rejected-for-a-job\">But if you do receive a rejection letter, here\'s what to do.</a>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000240\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/TSW_sample_cv_fdj01.png\" alt=\"sample resume\" width=\"1064\" height=\"649\" />\n<h2></h2>\n\n<hr />\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Related Reading</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job/\">How to Get a Job: The Step-by-Step Guide</a>\n<a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/how-to-write-a-cover-letter/\">How to Write a Winning Cover Letter</a>\n<a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/step-by-step-interview-guide/\">Your Step-by-Step Interview Guide</a></p>\n\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2><strong>Seven Crucial Parts of Your Perfect Resume</strong></h2>\n<span data-offset-key=\"1l6v3-0-0\">Most resumes follow a standard format. </span><span class=\"complexword\"><span data-offset-key=\"1l6v3-1-0\">However</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"1l6v3-2-0\">, there is room inside the form to highlight your best qualities. Here are seven items found in most resumes.</span>\n<h4>1. Identification</h4>\nThe classic way to begin a resume is to list your contact information  (name, address, phone, and email). You may also include the URL of any online professional profiles, such as LinkedIn, or the URL of your professional webpage.\n\n<span data-offset-key=\"5u0p0-0-0\">Do not include links to your Facebook, Twitter, or Instagram pages. Unless there is a specific reason you want an employer to view your personal posts. For example, you are applying for a photography job and you want an employer to see your photos. </span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"5u0p0-1-0\">Regardless, be aware that potential employers may search social media sites and the web to learn more about you online</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"5u0p0-2-0\">.</span>\n<h4>2. Objective Statement</h4>\nAn objective statement is a brief summary of your employment goals. These may include your desired industry, position, work environment, hours, and salary requirements. An objective statement may overlap with something you have written in your cover letter.\n\n<strong>Sample Objective Statement: “Certified high school history teacher with 5 years of classroom experience seeking full-time employment at a public school teaching</strong> U.S.<strong> and/or Global History.”</strong>\n<h4>3. Summary Statement</h4>\n<span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-0-0\">A summary statement is a brief encapsulation of your qualifications. It may also include your </span></span><span class=\"complexword\"><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-1-0\">objective</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-2-0\">. </span>\n\n<span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-2-0\">Evaluating a resume can be a subjective experience. An </span><span class=\"complexword\"><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-3-0\">objective</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-4-0\"> statement tells potential employers how to read and understand your resume. </span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-5-0\">A summary statement may be especially useful if your experience </span></span><span class=\"passivevoice\"><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-6-0\">is varied</span></span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-7-0\"> and diverse</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"58tfc-8-0\">. Or if your experience is not an obvious match for the position you’re seeking.</span>\n\n<strong>Sample Summary Statement: “Writer and editor seeking a mid-level full-time position in a digital marketing agency, especially in the entertainment, sports, or financial sectors.”</strong>\n<h4>4. Branding Statement</h4>\n<span data-offset-key=\"fvttd-0-0\">A branding statement is </span><span class=\"complexword\"><span data-offset-key=\"fvttd-1-0\">similar to</span></span> <span class=\"complexword\"><span data-offset-key=\"fvttd-3-0\">objective</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"fvttd-4-0\"> and summary statements. </span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"fvttd-5-0\">It borrows from the catchy, informal language of advertising, marketing, and social media</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"fvttd-6-0\">. Branding statements are popular among Millenials and people in creative industries.</span>\n\n<strong>Sample Branding Statement: “I make magic out of data and Excel spreadsheets.”</strong>\n<h4>5. Experience</h4>\nThe experience section of your resume encapsulates your employment history. Each entry should include your employer, job title, and start and end dates of your employment. An entry may also include three to five bullet points summarizing your primary roles and responsibilities. Typically, each bullet point begins with an action verb indicating a specific activity (e.g. designed, executed, managed). Entries should start with your current or most recent job and then proceed in reverse chronological order.\n\nAs a general rule, the more recent and/or substantial the job, the longer the entry should be.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000241\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/TSW_sample_cv_fdj02.png\" alt=\"Sample resume example 2\" width=\"1397\" height=\"931\" />\n<h4>6. Education</h4>\nThe education section of your resume covers your formal schooling. Each entry should include the school name, geographic location, dates attended, and degree achieved. For each entry include your major, minor, and any specialized areas of study. Entries should start with your highest level of education and then proceed in reverse chronological order (e.g. graduate school, college, high school).\n\nThis section may also include non-degree education, including certification, continuing education, grants, and fellowships.\n<h4>7. Skills, Hobbies, Volunteer and Philanthropic Work</h4>\n<span data-offset-key=\"fkfo6-0-0\">Some people also include skills, hobbies, and any philanthropic activity on their resumes. This is a great way to personalize their job applications. </span><span class=\"hardreadability\"><span data-offset-key=\"fkfo6-1-0\">This can be effective, but be careful about sharing too much personal information or irrelevant information</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"fkfo6-2-0\">. Save that for your social media page or online dating profile.</span>\n\n<span data-offset-key=\"6j69r-0-0\">Employers want to know about your professional qualifications first. Then, </span><span class=\"adverb\"><span data-offset-key=\"6j69r-1-0\">secondarily</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"6j69r-2-0\">, about activities that reflect </span><span class=\"adverb\"><span data-offset-key=\"6j69r-3-0\">positively</span></span><span data-offset-key=\"6j69r-4-0\"> on your character. And finally, only insofar as those activities reflect your potential as an employee. Charity walks and volunteering at a homeless shelter might fit the bill.</span>\n\nAvoid citing commonplace activities like cooking, gardening, pick-up basketball, or binge-watching <em>Game of Thrones</em>.  If you are unsure whether to include a hobby or activity, leave it off your resume. You can always mention it during the interview if an opportunity arises. (“Oh, you run? I ran the Chicago marathon last year.”) Better yet, share this information with your colleagues—<em>after</em> you get the job.\n<h2><strong>\nRules of Thumb for a Perfect Resume</strong></h2>\nResumes vary considerably but obey several general rules of thumb in terms of format. The five rules below are key to creating a perfect resume.\n\n<strong>Note: We created a <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/resume-builder/\">Resume Building Tool</a> to help to format your resumes. Check it out, absolutely free.</strong>\n<h4>1. Length</h4>\nA perfect resume should be no longer than one page. Additional information, such as publications or portfolios or work samples, should be appended separately.\n<h4>2. Font Size</h4>\nA resume should be written in a standard font (e.g. Times, Calibri, Cambia, <strong>no comic sans!</strong>). Size should be no smaller than 12-point and no larger than 14-point.\n<h4>3. Margins</h4>\nA resume should have 1-inch margins on all side (top, bottom, left and right).\n<h4>4. Layout</h4>\nAfter the opening, resumes should begin either with <strong>Education</strong> or<strong> Experience</strong>.  Begin with Education if you are a recent college graduate and/or if your education is among the most impressive of your qualifications. Begin with Experience if you are not a recent graduate and/or if your professional experience is more impressive than your education.\n<h4>5. Tone</h4>\nThe tone of a resume should be formal, with the exception of a branding statement, which may be more informal. If you are unsure of the tone you need to take, be more formal.\n<h2><strong>The Last Word</strong></h2>\nA perfect resume is your ticket to your next job. Treat it seriously and potential employers will treat you seriously. After you\'ve built a standout resume, review our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job/\">Complete Step-by-Step Guide to Getting a Job</a> to take the next step towards your new career.','My Perfect Resume: A Complete Guide','','publish','closed','open','','how-to-build-my-perfect-resume','','','2019-07-11 21:49:11','2019-07-11 21:49:11','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000225',0,'post','',0),(100000226,2,'2019-04-16 19:06:51','2019-04-16 19:06:51','Whether it\'s your first or it\'s new, getting a job is stressful. There are a lot of steps, and it can be hard to track your progress when you don\'t get feedback.<!--more-->\n\nThis step-by-step guide will help you organize your job search to make it less stressful and to help you get the job you want!\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000250\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/vanveenjf-1125254-unsplash_trucking.jpg\" alt=\"vanveenjf-1125254-unsplash_trucking\" width=\"1064\" height=\"629\" />\n<h2>What Do You Need From a Job?</h2>\nBefore you start applying for jobs, take some time to define your goals. This can be an intimidating step, but you can make it easier by creating a spreadsheet to order your priorities and opportunities. In the spreadsheet, ask the following questions:\n<ul>\n 	<li>What are your skills, and what skills would you like to learn?</li>\n 	<li>What are your requirements for salary and benefits, such as medical, dental, and retirement accounts? Another way of saying that is, what kind of job do you need to feel secure?</li>\n 	<li>Do you want to work full-time or part-time, do you need regular hours or a flexible schedule?</li>\n 	<li>Do you want to work in-house or remotely, how far would you commute, and are you willing to relocate?</li>\n</ul>\nUltimately, the more clarity you have about your goals in advance, the easier, more efficient, and more fruitful your job search will be.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000232\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer.jpg\" alt=\"glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer\" width=\"1064\" height=\"708\" />\n<h2><strong>The Science of Constructing Your Resume to Get a Job</strong></h2>\nA resume is the quickest way for an employer to assess your qualifications and decide whether to grant you an interview.\n\nA resume includes your educational history and professional experience, plus specific skills, responsibilities, and honors you may have accrued. Resume formats vary, and templates are widely available online.\n\nYour resume should be free from errors in spelling, grammar, and syntax.  Even small errors on a resume suggest a lack of seriousness about the job and give an employer an easy reason to reject your application.\n\nCreate the perfect resume with our guide on <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/how-to-build-the-perfect-resume\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How to Build the Perfect Resume</a>.\n<h2><strong>Improve Your Cover Letter. It\'ll help you get a job!</strong></h2>\nA cover letter is the first thing a potential employer reads – and potentially the last. If your cover letter is persuasive, the employer will read your resume. If your cover letter is not persuasive, an employer will not read your resume or consider your application. A cover letter should not simply repeat your resume but complement your resume with your personal story and context that will help the hiring manager decide if you’re a good fit.\n<h4>Effective cover letters all cover three basic questions:</h4>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Why do you want the job?</li>\n 	<li>How are you qualified?</li>\n 	<li>How would the employer benefit if you were hired?</li>\n</ol>\nEffective cover letters are not longer than one page. They vary widely in style and tone, but should always use correct spelling and grammar. Even small errors on a cover letter suggest a lack of seriousness about the job and give an employer an easy reason to reject your application.\n\nFor more, see our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/how-to-write-a-cover-letter/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How to Write a Winning Cover Letter</a> guide.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000231\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/nordwood-themes-359015-unsplash_social_media_networking.jpg\" alt=\"nordwood-themes-359015-unsplash_social_media_networking\" width=\"1064\" height=\"709\" />\n<h2><strong>Optimize Your Social Media</strong></h2>\nIf you’re looking for work, who you know is as important – perhaps more important – than what you know.\n\nIn a competitive marketplace, one of the easiest ways to find work and distinguish your application from similarly qualified candidates is through a personal connection. Social media is a powerful tool for researching and discovering jobs, and for connecting with people who may give you leads on employment opportunities.\n\nFacebook has <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/821597814598173/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">many group pages</a> dedicated to fostering communities of job seekers, and many companies will post job openings through their Twitter accounts. (NPR has a <a href=\"https://twitter.com/NPRjobs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Twitter account</a> dedicated to recruiting employees.)\n\nFacebook, Instagram and Twitter are also good places to build your personal brand. Employers often look at social media accounts to make sure candidates fit their company culture.\n<h3>LinkedIn</h3>\nLinkedIn offers users a way to make professional connections via social networks, using a system of degrees: People you know are 1<sup>st</sup> degree connections; people they know are 2<sup>nd</sup> degree connections, people they know are 3<sup>rd</sup> degree, and so on. For example, if you’re applying for a job at Example Company, Inc., you might learn that six of your friends (or acquaintances) work at that company.\n\nLinkedIn has a list of <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20140708162049-7239647-16-tips-to-optimize-your-linkedin-profile-and-enhance-your-personal-brand\">16 tips</a> to optimize your profile to make it stand out. The most results-oriented tips are:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Create a vanity URL for your profile. Did you know you can make the URL of your profile stand out? So instead of <a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/7xyz6709\">linkedin.com/7xyz6709</a>, you can have <a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/Joseph_Strummer\">www.linkedin.com/Joseph_Strummer</a>.</li>\n 	<li>Add symbols and bullets to your profile to make it more visually engaging.</li>\n 	<li>Ask for written recommendations from former employers and colleagues.</li>\n</ol>\nHow you use social media depends on your personal level of comfort with asking for help in a public setting. On one hand, you might post a general announcement on social media that you are looking for work. On the other, you might use social media to research jobs and contact people directly.  Regardless, your network is one of your most powerful resources in finding a job, and it should be leveraged.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000218\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/cytonn-photography-604681-unsplash_handshake.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by Cytonn Photography on Unsplash\" width=\"1064\" height=\"710\" />\n<h2><strong>Learn How to Network Like a Pro</strong></h2>\nConnecting with people on social media is one effective way to find employment; meeting with people in person can be even more effective.\n\nIn a crowded and competitive marketplace, people like to hire people they know and/or those who come referred. If you’re seeking work, arrange informational meetings with people in your industry, people in related industries, and anyone you know whose career you admire and respect. Treat these meetings not as social encounters, but as informal interviews.\n\nDo your homework on the person with whom you are meeting. Come prepared with a sense of your goals and a list of specific questions. Don’t expect a job offer on the spot any more than you would expect a marriage proposal on a first date. If you meet at a coffee shop or restaurant, you should pay the bill to show gratitude.\n\nFrom social media to building relationships off-lines, sharpen your skills with our article <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/networking-complete-guide/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Everything You Need to Know to Master Networking</a>.\n<h2><strong>Know The Applicant Tracking System</strong></h2>\nBecause it’s so easy to search and apply for a large number of jobs online, employers are flooded with more applications than they can handle. Accordingly, companies initially screen applicants’ resumes using “bots” – computer programs with algorithms that search for keywords and particular qualifications.\n\nResumes that make the cut are then forwarded to an actual human being for review. To boost the odds of your resume standing out from the digital crowd, keep it clear, straightforward, organized, and logical. Study the job description and make sure that your resume includes keywords from that description, including specific skills and experiences.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000202\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/tim-gouw-79563-unsplash_interview_women_business_01.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by Tim Gouw on Unsplash\" width=\"1064\" height=\"711\" />\n<h2><strong>Acing Your Interviews </strong></h2>\nIf you are invited to a job interview, you are probably qualified to do that job. Accordingly, the goal of an interview is to convince your interviewers to hire you over other similarly qualified applicants.\n\nRemember that an interview is a two-way street: you are interviewing your prospective employers as much as they are interviewing you. Be prepared to speak – but also to listen. Come prepared to present yourself, answer questions, and ask your employer questions. Be sure to dress appropriately to indicate the seriousness of your intent.\n\nEven if you are interviewing at a workplace with a casual dress code, you can almost never be overdressed for an interview, but you can certainly be under-dressed.\n<h2><strong>Follow-ups </strong></h2>\n<strong>Follow-ups</strong> are a crucial way to stay on someone’s radar. Every time you meet, talk, or correspond with a person during your job hunt, follow up promptly in writing.\n\nThere are a couple of things you should keep in mind when following up on a job lead.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Be brief, clear, and direct. Ask specific questions that require specific answers.</li>\n 	<li>Your tone should be respectful and grateful, and not pushy or entitled.</li>\n</ul>\nDo not expect a prompt reply –most professionals are busy and drowning in email— but if you do not hear back from someone in a few days, it’s appropriate to send a brief, gentle reminder.\n<h2>Thank You Notes May Help You Get a Job</h2>\nAfter every interview, send your interviewers a thank-you note. While such a note may seem trivial, it’s a crucial component of finding a job.\n\n<strong>Thank-you notes</strong> are an opportunity to reiterate your interest in the job (if you are still interested) and to communicate your thoughtfulness and graciousness. Both will help you stand out from other candidates.\n\nKeep the notes brief, clear, and free of errors.  Do not expect a response. Even if you do not get the job for which you interviewed, a thank-you note helps leaves the door open for future employment opportunities. From mental preparation to reinforcing a good impression, dive deep into interview prep with our <a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/guides/step-by-step-interview-guide\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Step-by-Step Interview Guide</a>.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-100000199\" src=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/johanna-buguet-1203379-unsplash02.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"6720\" height=\"4480\" />\n<h2><strong>Negotiating Your Offer</strong></h2>\nDo not accept the first job offer you receive. Employers will almost always “lowball,” offering a prospective employee less money than they are ultimately willing to pay.\n\nAfter you receive an offer, review your own compensation history. Research the compensation for similar jobs, using sites like GlassDoor, and honestly assess your financial needs and cost of living expenses. Then make a counteroffer.\n<h3>Do Not Accept Your First Offer</h3>\nIf the employer has made a reasonable offer, your counter-offer might range from 10-25 percent more.  So if you were offered an annual salary of $100,000, you might ask for $110,000 to $125,000. Remember, negotiating your initial job offer is your best chance–and often your only chance—to increase your compensation. Do <em>not</em> accept your first offer.\n<h2><strong>The Last Word</strong></h2>\nMost of all, when looking for a job remember that perseverance and smarts will see you through. Planning and preparation are 99% of what it takes to take your career to the next level!','How to Get a Job: the Step-by-Step Guide','','publish','closed','open','','the-complete-step-by-step-guide-to-getting-a-job','','','2019-07-11 21:48:39','2019-07-11 21:48:39','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000226',0,'post','',0),(100000227,4,'2019-04-15 15:46:48','2019-04-15 15:46:48','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','amy-hirschi-1416711-unsplash_networking_meeting','','','2019-04-15 15:47:06','2019-04-15 15:47:06','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/amy-hirschi-1416711-unsplash_networking_meeting.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000229,4,'2019-04-15 15:49:15','2019-04-15 15:49:15','Two professionals chat amiably at a networking event','Two professionals chat amiably at a networking event','','inherit','closed','closed','','amy-hirschi-1416711-unsplash_networking_meeting02','','','2019-06-21 11:58:44','2019-06-21 11:58:44','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/amy-hirschi-1416711-unsplash_networking_meeting02.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000231,4,'2019-04-15 16:04:29','2019-04-15 16:04:29','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','nordwood-themes-359015-unsplash_social_media_networking','','','2019-04-15 16:04:43','2019-04-15 16:04:43','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/nordwood-themes-359015-unsplash_social_media_networking.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000232,4,'2019-04-15 17:57:38','2019-04-15 17:57:38','','glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer','','inherit','closed','closed','','glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer','','','2019-04-15 17:57:47','2019-04-15 17:57:47','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/glenn-carstens-peters-203007-unsplash_write_computer.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000233,4,'2019-04-15 18:03:55','2019-04-15 18:03:55','','monica-melton-467245-unsplash_mentor','','inherit','closed','closed','','monica-melton-467245-unsplash_mentor','','','2019-04-15 18:04:03','2019-04-15 18:04:03','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/monica-melton-467245-unsplash_mentor.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000234,4,'2019-04-15 18:15:37','2019-04-15 18:15:37','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','jobz-tyler-1397802-unsplash_elevator_pitch','','','2019-04-15 18:15:49','2019-04-15 18:15:49','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/jobz-tyler-1397802-unsplash_elevator_pitch.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000235,4,'2019-04-15 18:17:55','2019-04-15 18:17:55','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','marten-newhall-226045-unsplash_eyes_suit_glass','','','2019-04-15 18:18:03','2019-04-15 18:18:03','',100000224,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/marten-newhall-226045-unsplash_eyes_suit_glass.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000237,4,'2019-04-15 20:00:18','2019-04-15 20:00:18','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','joanna-kosinska-129039-unsplash_write_pencil','','','2019-04-15 20:00:28','2019-04-15 20:00:28','',100000225,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/joanna-kosinska-129039-unsplash_write_pencil.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000239,4,'2019-04-15 20:34:50','2019-04-15 20:34:50','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','alejandro-escamilla-7-unsplash_writer_writing','','','2019-04-15 20:34:56','2019-04-15 20:34:56','',100000225,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alejandro-escamilla-7-unsplash_writer_writing.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000240,4,'2019-04-15 21:10:03','2019-04-15 21:10:03','','TSW_sample_cv_fdj01','','inherit','closed','closed','','tsw_sample_cv_fdj01','','','2019-04-15 21:10:13','2019-04-15 21:10:13','',100000225,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/TSW_sample_cv_fdj01.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(100000241,4,'2019-04-15 21:55:11','2019-04-15 21:55:11','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','tsw_sample_cv_fdj02','','','2019-04-15 21:55:33','2019-04-15 21:55:33','',100000225,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/TSW_sample_cv_fdj02.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(100000242,4,'2019-04-15 22:13:37','2019-04-15 22:13:37','','adeolu-eletu-38649-unsplash_business_job','','inherit','closed','closed','','adeolu-eletu-38649-unsplash_business_job','','','2019-04-15 22:13:45','2019-04-15 22:13:45','',100000226,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/adeolu-eletu-38649-unsplash_business_job.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000250,4,'2019-04-16 13:20:31','2019-04-16 13:20:31','','','','inherit','closed','closed','','vanveenjf-1125254-unsplash_trucking','','','2019-04-16 13:20:40','2019-04-16 13:20:40','',100000226,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/vanveenjf-1125254-unsplash_trucking.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000264,2,'2019-04-17 14:32:04','2019-04-17 14:32:04',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','100000264','','','2019-04-17 14:32:04','2019-04-17 14:32:04','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000264',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(100000318,2,'2019-06-19 09:00:25','2019-06-19 09:00:25','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In recent years, there is lots of talk surrounding automation in the transportation industry. Yet, the days of self-driving trucks remain in the future. If you enjoy driving and don’t mind spending long stretches of time away from home, you\'re in demand. A typical starting salary around $30,000 makes truck driving jobs an attractive career path. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The complex and robust trucking industry offers a wide range of jobs. These jobs vary in earning potential and requirements. It is imperative that you do your research before attempting to sift through thousands of job postings. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Below is a list of the highest-paying truck driving jobs to date. Note that your job satisfaction will rely on other factors beyond compensation for your labor. But we assume that for most individuals, it’s among one of the most important factors when choosing truck driving jobs. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>How much do Truck Driving Jobs pay?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many lucrative truck driving jobs within specialized niches, and driving jobs with top trucking companies. In 2017, the top 10% of truck drivers brought home over $64,000. While the median salary of truck drivers was $42,480, per a report by <a href=\"https://www.truckerstraining.com/how-much-do-truck-drivers-make-ultimate-guide/\">Trucker’s Training</a>. Out of 4,230 salaries reported on <a href=\"https://www.glassdoor.com/Salaries/us-truck-driver-salary-SRCH_IL.0,2_IN1_KO3,15.htm\">Glassdoor</a>, the average base pay for truck drivers in the United States is $57,872 per year. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That\'s an incredible rate! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>Average Annual Pay Rate for Truck Drivers</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to the <a href=\"https://www.bls.gov/ooh/transportation-and-material-moving/heavy-and-tractor-trailer-truck-drivers.htm\">Bureau of Labor Statistics</a>, the average annual pay rate for a truck driver in the U.S. was $45,330 as of August, 2018. And the average hourly rate was $21.80. Figures differed by state and region. Washington D.C. tops the list at an average salary of $58,388 per year and $30 per hour. While West Virginia was at the bottom with an annual truck driving salary of $44,330 and an average hourly rate of $18.55. Currently, the federal minimum wage is $7.25, although 29 states and D.C. have moved their minimum wages above that level.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a handful of variables that will aid in determining the amount you can expect to earn truck driving. These include the type of trucking, such as over the road (OTR), short haul, freight, or team driving. Niches in trucking, such as oversized loads, car haulers, or tanker work, will also factor into pay. Alongside: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>The particular trucking company that employs you </li><li>Your experience as a truck driver, measured by your years of CDL driving experience</li><li>Where you live. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator is-style-default\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=truck%20driver\">Find and Apply to Truck Driving Jobs </a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>How do you get your first Truck Driving Job?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Truck driving jobs do not always need post secondary education. In fact, they require a modest training time compared to other occupations. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To drive a Commercial Motor Vehicle (CMV), you will need to obtain a Commercial Driver’s License (CDL) through the Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) in the state you reside in. Additionally, you will need to meet federal and state requirements, as well as company qualifications, to get started. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>What are the requirements for a CDL?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:yoast/how-to-block {\"jsonDescription\":\"Requirements for getting a CDL in most states are:\",\"steps\":[{\"id\":\"how-to-step-1560890120552\",\"name\":[\" Being 21 years of age. \",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"\"],\"text\":[\"While a standard driver\'s license can be earned a number of years before, CDLs are given to more experienced and mature drivers.\"],\"jsonName\":\" Being 21 years of age. \",\"jsonText\":\"While a standard driver\'s license can be earned a number of years before, CDLs are given to more experienced and mature drivers.\"},{\"id\":\"how-to-step-1560890217508\",\"name\":[\" A clean record (or a recent clean record). \",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"\"],\"text\":[\"Felonious activities can often cause employers to pause when considering a candidate. However, for many truck driving jobs, employers will still consider applicants with a criminal history.\"],\"jsonName\":\" A clean record (or a recent clean record). \",\"jsonText\":\"Felonious activities can often cause employers to pause when considering a candidate. However, for many truck driving jobs, employers will still consider applicants with a criminal history.\"},{\"id\":\"how-to-step-1560890221810\",\"name\":[\" No recent DUIs.\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"\"],\"text\":[\"Driving a Commercial Motor Vehicle takes a lot of focus. DUIs show a level of irresponsibility that could lead to people getting hurt out on the road. \"],\"jsonName\":\" No recent DUIs.\",\"jsonText\":\"Driving a Commercial Motor Vehicle takes a lot of focus. DUIs show a level of irresponsibility that could lead to people getting hurt out on the road. \"},{\"id\":\"how-to-step-1560890229055\",\"name\":[\" No other major violations like reckless driving.   \"],\"text\":[\"Similar to above, employers want their truck drivers to be responsible drivers. Reckless driving puts the driver at risk, but it also endangers other drivers on the road. It also creates a lot of risk for the company.\"],\"jsonName\":\" No other major violations like reckless driving.   \",\"jsonText\":\"Similar to above, employers want their truck drivers to be responsible drivers. Reckless driving puts the driver at risk, but it also endangers other drivers on the road. It also creates a lot of risk for the company.\"}],\"defaultDurationText\":\"Time needed:\"} -->\n<div class=\"schema-how-to wp-block-yoast-how-to-block\"><p class=\"schema-how-to-description\">Requirements for getting a CDL in most states are:</p> <ol class=\"schema-how-to-steps\"><li class=\"schema-how-to-step\"><strong class=\"schema-how-to-step-name\"> Being 21 years of age. <br/></strong> <p class=\"schema-how-to-step-text\">While a standard driver\'s license can be earned a number of years before, CDLs are given to more experienced and mature drivers.</p> </li><li class=\"schema-how-to-step\"><strong class=\"schema-how-to-step-name\"> A clean record (or a recent clean record). <br/></strong> <p class=\"schema-how-to-step-text\">Felonious activities can often cause employers to pause when considering a candidate. However, for many truck driving jobs, employers will still consider applicants with a criminal history.</p> </li><li class=\"schema-how-to-step\"><strong class=\"schema-how-to-step-name\"> No recent DUIs.<br/></strong> <p class=\"schema-how-to-step-text\">Driving a Commercial Motor Vehicle takes a lot of focus. DUIs show a level of irresponsibility that could lead to people getting hurt out on the road. </p> </li><li class=\"schema-how-to-step\"><strong class=\"schema-how-to-step-name\"> No other major violations like reckless driving.   </strong> <p class=\"schema-how-to-step-text\">Similar to above, employers want their truck drivers to be responsible drivers. Reckless driving puts the driver at risk, but it also endangers other drivers on the road. It also creates a lot of risk for the company.</p> </li></ol></div>\n<!-- /wp:yoast/how-to-block -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The main requirements to get a CDL in most states are: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Being 21 years of age. </li><li>A clean record (or a recent clean record). </li><li>No recent DUIs.</li><li>No other major violations like reckless driving. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once these basic requirements are met, potential truck drivers will need to attend truck driving school CDL training. Some schools may like to see a diploma or GED before applying, and some truck driving companies require them for hiring. But most companies will not ask to see a diploma or GED. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Information about Tuition and Fees for your CDL</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each truck driving program differs in tuition and fees, but have options for financial aid. The time commitment ranges from 30 days to 10 weeks. Although some can extend to a full year. At the end of the program, you will need to pass the state CDL exam. The CDL Exam consists of a written test and a road skills test, as well as the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Regulation (FMCSR) exam. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After that, it’s time to get hired. Conveniently, many truck driving schools offer job placement services. The top five of the jobs listed below have reported annual incomes well above $100,000 per year. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>Best Truck Driving Jobs <br></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:yoast/faq-block {\"questions\":[{\"id\":\"faq-question-1560888680644\",\"question\":[\" Best Trucking Jobs (By Salary)  \"],\"answer\":[\" Tanker Hauler\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Hazardous Materials Driver\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Oversized Loads\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Ice Road Trucker\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Specialty Car Transport Driver\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Team Driver\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Truck Company Owner/Operator \",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"OTR Driver\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Trucking Industry Recruiter\",{\"type\":\"br\",\"props\":{\"children\":[]}},\"Trucking School Instructor \"],\"jsonQuestion\":\" Best Trucking Jobs (By Salary)  \",\"jsonAnswer\":\" Tanker HaulerHazardous Materials DriverOversized LoadsIce Road TruckerSpecialty Car Transport DriverTeam DriverTruck Company Owner/Operator OTR DriverTrucking Industry RecruiterTrucking School Instructor \"}]} -->\n<div class=\"schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block\"><div class=\"schema-faq-section\"><strong class=\"schema-faq-question\"> Best Trucking Jobs (By Salary)  </strong> <p class=\"schema-faq-answer\"> Tanker Hauler<br/>Hazardous Materials Driver<br/>Oversized Loads<br/>Ice Road Trucker<br/>Specialty Car Transport Driver<br/>Team Driver<br/>Truck Company Owner/Operator <br/>OTR Driver<br/>Trucking Industry Recruiter<br/>Trucking School Instructor </p> </div> </div>\n<!-- /wp:yoast/faq-block -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To increase your ability to make more money truck driving, you should consider specialized work or obtaining endorsements. These may give you the ability to transport hazardous materials, to win a leg up against other candidates. \n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','10 Best Truck Driving Jobs for Earning Serious Cash','','publish','closed','open','','10-best-truck-driving-jobs-for-earning-serious-cash','','','2019-07-11 21:49:58','2019-07-11 21:49:58','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000318',0,'post','',0),(100000319,2,'2019-06-12 18:44:52','2019-06-12 18:44:52','','job-promotion','You deserve this promotion!','inherit','closed','closed','','job-promotion','','','2019-06-12 18:45:25','2019-06-12 18:45:25','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/job-promotion.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000331,2,'2019-06-18 19:15:14','2019-06-18 19:15:14','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For those seeking a career in the trucking industry, receiving a Commercial Driver’s License (CDL) is a first step in securing a well-paying job. In fact, trucker drivers can make over six figures in some specialized segments of the industry. Especially with top trucking companies. Most of these jobs will require that you go to school for CDL training, and then pass the required exams. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>Why do you need a CDL?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Obtaining a CDL will give you the ability to operate large, heavy, or hazardous material vehicles in commerce. They are necessary due to the nature of driving commercial motor vehicles (CMVs). CMVs are primarily tractor-trailers, or Longer Combination Vehicles (LCVs). CDLs show that you have the skills and knowledge beyond driving lightweight vehicle. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CDLs were first specified by the federal government upon the passing of the Commercial Motor Vehicle Safety Act of 1986. This act classified three main types of CDL licenses: Class A, B and C. This act aimed to prevent traffic deaths and accidents. It also intended to make the roads safer by licensing trained and qualified drivers. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1992, the CMV Safety Act became law, requiring all drivers to have a CDL to operate a CMV. Testing standards for CDL licensing are enforced by the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA). Written and practical tests can be taken from the State or an approved testing facility. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?&amp;subaff4=truck%20driving\">Find Truck Driving Jobs Near you</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Get your commercial drivers license in 9 steps:  </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>Have a state-issued driver’s license</li><li>Age requirements</li><li>Get a Commercial Driver’s Permit</li><li>Read your CDL manual</li><li>Attend a Commercial Drivers License Program</li><li>Identify applicable exceptions</li><li>Pass a knowledge exam</li><li>Pass a skills test</li><li>Extra requirements may be applicable depending on the state that you live in</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>Department of Transportation Medical Examination</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The DOT Medical Examination is a physical examination conducted by a licensed “medical examiner.” You can find these examiners on the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration (FMCSA) National Registret, per <a href=\"https://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/medical/driver-medical-requirements/dot-medical-exam-and-commercial-motor-vehicle-certification\">FMSCA</a>. A “medical examiner” includes a variety of doctors. Doctors of medicine, doctors of osteopathy, physician assistants, advanced practice nurses and also doctors of chiropractic. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After you pass the exam, it is valid for up to two years. Also, upon deciding if the candidate is qualified to drive a CMV, the medical examiner will supply one copy of the results and complete a Medical Examiner’s Certificate. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>What is the difference between Class A CDL and Class B CDL?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before enlisting in a CDL course of taking the exam, you must know which CDL you need for your desired job. The type of CDL you get will dictate which kind of CMV you can operate. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Class A CDLs allow you to drive any commercial motor vehicle, with a few exceptions. For example, you will need to receive necessary endorsements to drive a hazmat vehicle, a school bus, and other vehicles. But for those who want to drive an 18 wheeler, or a semi truck, a Class A is the way to go. <br>In technical terms, a Class A CDL is necessary to operate any combination of vehicles with a gross weight rating of 26,001 or more pounds (11,794 kg), including a towed vehicle with a gross weight of 10,000 pounds (4,546 kg) or more. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A Class B CDL allows you to drive a single vehicle that has a gross vehicle weight rating of 26,001 pounds or more and is pulling a trailer with a gross vehicle rating of under 10,000 pounds. <br>It is important to note that the Class A, B and C licenses distinguish by manufacturer weight rating. Meaning the total weight of the vehicle and everything in it and on it, such as the passengers, cargo and loads. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br>Financing your CDL process</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While a career in truck driving can be a lucrative one, some may get discouraged from pursuing their CDL training once they look into costs. On a positive note, paying for it all yourself up front isn’t necessary for many people. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like other educational programs, many CDL training courses provide financial aid. This financial aid comes in the form of scholarships, grants and loans. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Individual states provide grant money for CDL schools from the FMCSA, with the initiative to create safer roads and highways. Some students receive grants under the Workforce Investment Act. They may also receive the Trade Adjustment Assistance (TAA) grant for displaced workers. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For loans, the Free Applications for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) works for some CDL schools. Make sure before you register that your school qualifies. It’s important to note that Pell grants are designed for students from lower income brackets. They only apply for public CDL schools, and will not be given to shortened CDL programs under 24 weeks. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you served in the military, you may qualify for the GI Bill, which provides an educational funding benefit. <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Depending on your employer, certain trucking companies have started to offer financial aid. They assist people in getting their CDL due to a severe shortage of workers in certain high-demand industries. This type of financial aid can vary. It may include sponsoring the training in exchange for a one-year work commitment. They may also pay for lodging, provide loans, and other forms of help, according to <a href=\"https://www.sageschools.com/ten-best-options-to-pay-for-cdl-training-how-do-i-pay-for-truck-driving-school/\">Sage Truck Driving Schools</a>.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','How to get a Commercial Driver’s License (CDL)','','publish','closed','open','','how-to-get-a-commercial-drivers-license-cdl','','','2019-07-11 21:49:49','2019-07-11 21:49:49','',0,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/?p=100000331',0,'post','',0),(100000333,2,'2019-06-18 19:20:01','2019-06-18 19:20:01','A commercial truck drives up the bed of a valley between two hills. ','rodrigo-abreu-565091-unsplash','','inherit','closed','closed','','rodrigo-abreu-565091-unsplash','','','2019-06-18 19:39:24','2019-06-18 19:39:24','',100000331,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/rodrigo-abreu-565091-unsplash.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000338,2,'2019-06-18 20:06:25','2019-06-18 20:06:25','A white truck sits under an overpass. The top of the truck is being hit with light from the sun. From the passenger side window, you see an arm holding a US olympic team shirt.','charles-271643-unsplash','','inherit','closed','closed','','charles-271643-unsplash','','','2019-06-18 20:32:07','2019-06-18 20:32:07','',100000318,'https://www.finddreamjobs.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/charles-271643-unsplash.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100000359,5,'2019-07-02 17:52:01','2019-07-02 17:52:01','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=work%20from%20home\">Working from home</a> is an ideal way for millions of people to achieve the perfect work-life balance. And with the world becoming more and more digital, the time for work from home jobs is now. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are thousands of part-time and full-time opportunities available year round. Work from home jobs provide: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Increased flexibility.</li><li>The opportunity to work on your own terms. </li><li>The ability to work from the comfort of your living room. </li><li>And a chance to skip that tedious morning commute. 🙌<br></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to a 2017 study conducted by <a href=\"https://www.fundera.com\">FundEra.com</a>, 86% of professionals said they are most productive when working alone. They also think a flexible, remote, or telecommuting job would make them more productive throughout the day. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The study concluded with the most important reasons why job hunters are seeking work from home jobs. The leading reasons being scheduling flexibility, less distractions, higher wages, and the absence of office politics.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So whether you’re trying to save money, reduce stress, or toss that 9-5 life out the window...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are our<strong> Top 13 work from home jobs of 2019.&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>1. Call Center Representative&nbsp;</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None. People who are fluent in more than one language do have an advantage 😉</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$15 to $18 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you enjoy engaging with others and providing assistance, being a call center representative may be the perfect job for you.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Call center representatives are responsible for using their knowledge of the company products and services to assist customers with any questions, concerns, or problems they may have.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Work from home call center representative jobs are a consistent way for you to make some good money from the comfort of your home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=call%20center%20representative\">Look for Call Center Representative Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>2. Virtual Assistant</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>Up to $29 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you enjoy social interaction, providing assistance, and working with a variety of clients, you might want to look into becoming a virtual assistant.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Virtual Assistants</strong> are responsible for responding to emails and phone calls, organizing meetings,scheduling travel accommodations, and attending to any other needs the client has.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the biggest benefits of being a remote virtual assistant is the ability to work with <em>multiple clients</em>. Many experienced virtual assistants take on 2 or 3 clients and work with both simultaneously, leading to <em>2 to 3 times the money</em>, and a full day’s work from the comfort of their home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=virtual%20assistant\">Look for Virtual Assistant Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>3. Appointment Setting</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$18 to $22&nbsp; per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you like working with clients and being a vital part of a team, becoming a work from home appointment setter could be the job for you. Appointment setters typically work alongside a company’s sales team to set up meetings with prospective customers and clients.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Appointment setter’s don’t only set up meetings all day, they also confirm leads for the company and reach out to prospective clients directly to set up future sales calls!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=appointment%20setting\">Look for Appointment Setting Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>4. Medical Transcription</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$15 to $20 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Transcription is another viable option for anyone who enjoys typing, and wants the ability to work for multiple clients at once. Becoming a transcriptionist from home is an easy way to make some <em>side cash</em>, or, if you do want to take on multiple clients, it can become a full time work from home job. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Transcriptionists are responsible for typing out a transcript for <strong>audio and video files</strong>, such as meeting videos, podcasts, and lectures.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’d like to specialize in a certain field such as legal transcription, you could make even <em>more </em>money by becoming a full time transcriptionist within a few months!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=medical%20transcription\">Look for Medical Transcription Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>5. Customer Service Agent</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None for entry level positions. <em>Additional experience and training may be required for mid and upper level management positions.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>Up to $15 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another great work from home opportunity is becoming a customer service agent. Similar to a tech support representative, this position is a great full or part time opportunity and provides flexible hours and good pay.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A typical customer service agent’s responsibilities include answering calls from customers regarding customer service complaints, requesting assistance locating something, or asking about a product’s features and options.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Becoming a Customer Service Agent provides workers with the opportunity to make a lot of extra money on the side, earn a full time living, and can even open up further work from home opportunities with a company.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=customer%20service%20agent\">Look for Customer Service Agent Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>6. Amazon From Home</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None for entry level positions. <em>Additional experience and training may be required for mid and upper level positions.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>Up to $32 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amazon from home jobs are one of the most unique work from home opportunities available right now, due to its extremely wide range of available positions. Amazon offers hundreds of jobs in any and every field you can imagine. Options range from<em> customer service</em> to <em>advertising and marketing specialists</em>, and everything in between!<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Working from home with Amazon is an amazing way to <em>make good money</em> and work a meaningful job for a massive company that is innovating and creating new opportunities each and every day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=amazon%20from%20home\">Look for Amazon From Home Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>7. Bookkeeping</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>No experience is required. <em>Online training courses and/or a certification are trouble-free and can increase your likelihood of landing clients.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$20 to $36/hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you like numbers, making charts, and maintaining records, bookkeeping might be the perfect work from home job for you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bookkeeping is a very profitable and flexible way to <strong>make a full time living</strong> or some extra cash on the side, and doesn’t require anything but some basic accounting skills and a computer.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bookkeeping jobs are especially abundant because of the nature of small businesses. Every small business needs a bookkeeper, and outsourcing the job to a remote bookkeeper is much more efficient than bringing on a full time employee.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Similar to being a virtual assistant, remote bookkeepers can take on multiple clients and make some serious money while doing so.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=bookkeeping\">Look for Bookkeeping Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>8. Online Tutor</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>Bachelor’s degree in any subject is <em>typically</em> required</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$19 to $25</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Online tutoring jobs from home typically require applicants to have a Bachelor\'s degree, but each company’s requirements are different.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Online tutoring gives people the opportunity to work<strong> full or part time</strong> and typically has very flexible hours. Like many jobs on this list, as an online tutor you are able to take on multiple clients and clock a lot of hours if you want to.<em> The world is your oyster</em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=online%20tutor\">Look for Online Tutor Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>9. Apple From Home</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>Bachelor’s degree in any subject is <em>typically</em> required.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$19 to $25</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary: </strong>Much like Amazon, Apple is now offering thousands of work from home positions. Apple’s openings are primarily for advisor positions, but they offer tons of other opportunities such as software engineering, managerial roles, and salespeople.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This category is very broad because the apple from home movement is still relatively new, and there are so many different positions available that it’s hard to discuss the usual responsibilities of the role. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What we can say, however, is that Apple is a viable opportunity for anyone looking for a part-time or full-time role dealing with technology and social interaction. So, if that describes you, Apple from home could be a match made in heaven!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=apple%20work%20from%20home\">Look for Apple Work From Home Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>10. Accountant</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>Most employers require a bachelor’s degree in accounting or a related field, prior accounting experience would certainly benefit you in terms of pay, advancement, and opportunity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>Up to $40 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Work from home accounting is relatively specific, but, that doesn’t mean it isn’t still a great option. Accounting is one of the few jobs on our list that most likely require&nbsp; degree in a specific field, but if you happen to have been an accounting or finance major in college, this could be a great fit for you.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Accounting from home allows you to do the job you love from the comfort of your own home, avoid office politics, and skip the dreaded morning commute. Any and all work can be done at home with a computer, and any necessary communications can be done with company-wide instant messengers and/or video conferencing software.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you’re fresh out of college or looking for a serious change of scenery, there are plenty of companies actively searching for a work from home accountant.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=remote%20accountant\">Look for Accountant Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><br><strong>11. Product Tester</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$12 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Product Testing is one of the most fun and unique ways to make money from home. Product testing can involve testing makeup, video games, technology, food, and everything in between.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a work from home product tester, new or updated products are sent to your house for you to test. You are responsible for testing the product in depth, and then typing up a feedback report for the company depending on what they ask you. Usually, the reports focus on how the product looked, if it worked, how it made you feel, your initial reaction, and a host of other questions depending on the product and the company.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=product%20tester\">Look for Product Tester Jobs</a><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>12. Travel Agent&nbsp;</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$15 to $21 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Travel agents are responsible for assisting clients in making travel plans, whether it’s for business or vacation.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Work from home travel agents are typically responsible for booking flights, rental cars, hotels, excursions, and providing a detailed outline of what a trip will consist of day to day. Travel agents can take on multiple clients, and are typically able to <em>work flexible hours</em> as a result.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?subaff4=travel%20agent\">Look for Travel Agent Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>13. Editor</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Experience Required: </strong>None, but past writing, editing, or blogging experience always helps!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Average Pay: </strong>$11 to $24 per hour</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summary:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the constant demand for content, competent and passionate editors are in very high demand. Work from home editor positions are great for anyone with a passion or a knack for writing, blogging, and catching and correcting mistakes. Editor’s can work freelance or directly for an online newspaper or blog. Freelance editing positions are a great way to make extra money on the side, and working for a company is a very suitable way to make a living from home.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As an editor, your responsibilities would include reviewing articles and blog posts that are going to be submitted soon, catching and fixing any mistakes, and making sure the information provided and the sourcing is correct. If any of this interests you and you are looking for a flexible position with good pay, becoming a remote editor might just be the perfect job for you.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.finddreamjobs.com/jobs/?&amp;subaff4=remote%20editor\">Look for Editor Jobs</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:h